  <title>Cogl.MatrixEntry</title>
  <synopsis><code>
const Cogl = imports.gi.Cogl;

let matrixEntry = new Cogl.MatrixEntry();
  </code></synopsis>
  <p>Represents a single immutable transformation that was retrieved
from a <link xref="Cogl.MatrixStack"/> using <link xref="Cogl.MatrixStack.get_entry"/>.</p>  <p>Internally a <link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry"/> represents a single matrix
operation (such as "rotate", "scale", "translate") which is applied
to the transform of a single parent entry.</p>  <p>Using the <link xref="Cogl.MatrixStack"/> api effectively builds up a graph of
these immutable <link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry"/> structures whereby operations
that can be shared between multiple transformations will result
in shared <link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry"/> nodes in the graph.</p>  <p>When a <link xref="Cogl.MatrixStack"/> is first created it references one
<link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry"/> that represents a single "load identity"
operation. This serves as the root entry and all operations
that are then applied to the stack will extend the graph
starting from this root "load identity" entry.</p>  <p>Given the typical usage model for a <link xref="Cogl.MatrixStack"/> and the way
the entries are built up while traversing a scenegraph then in most
cases where an application is interested in comparing two
transformations for equality then it is enough to simply compare
two <link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry"/> pointers directly. Technically this can lead
to false negatives that could be identified with a deeper
comparison but often these false negatives are unlikely and
don't matter anyway so this enables extremely cheap comparisons.</p>  <p>&lt;note&gt;<link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry"/>&lt;!-- --&gt;s are reference counted using
<link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry.ref"/> and <link xref="Cogl.MatrixEntry.unref"/> not with
<link xref="Cogl.Object.ref"/> and <link xref="Cogl.Object.unref"/>.&lt;/note&gt;</p>

